Turkey expands diplomatic horizon
Long before Turkey wanted to join the European Union, the European powers were interested in penetrating deep into the hinterland of Turkey.
On the eastern side of the Bosporus, perhaps just 20 steps within Asia, stands one of the finest relics of this failed imperial endeavor.
The Hydarpasha station was designed by the two German architects Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu in Neo-Renaissance style.
At least that's what the guides tell you.
The building sits at the end of the platforms with a tower at each corner of the front and thus looks like any provincial German City Hall.
The rock is dirty.
The whole building falls apart about
But once you are inside the curved ticket counter, there is no doubt about the grandeur of the project whose westernmost access was this.
The station was opened in August 1908 by a German consortium, the Anatolia-Bagdad Society.
Germany, which was a late-commissioner in the imperialist game, had before implementing its ambitions to dominate the Middle East, by means of a train connection to Damascus, Baghdad, and further beyond what is now Saudi Arabia.
But Germany's imperialist plans were lame during the First World War.
His railroad tracks were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his Arabs.
The relative isolation from its surrounding region, created by the insurmountable borders of the cold war, has disappeared.
British forces moved out of Egypt and urged the Turks and their Germans allies from Palestine and Syria
And there was also bad news for the Hyderpasha station.
In 1917, an ammunition train flew into the air, destroying the artful roof.
Turkish sources say it was sabotage.
Since then it has slowly disintegrated, largely overlooked by history.
Today, however, this railway line serves, at least symbolically, as a gateway to Anatolia and everything to the east of it to highlight the expansion of the diplomatic horizon of Turkey.
The ruling Justice and Development Party, the AKP, has introduced a whole new foreign policy for the country.
Relative isolation from neighbouring regions, created by the Cold War borders, has disappeared.
Now there is a policy of rapprochement.
Remarkably, the Turkish Government has good relations with Israel and Syria, with the Palestinian factions Hamas and Fatah, with Iran and Iraq, and, of course, with the European Union and the United States.
In order to assess the key figures of this new foreign policy, I have climbed the night train to the Turkish capital Ankara to visit one of the ACP's leading foreign policy experts, the Turkish MEP Suat Kiniklioglu.
The next morning, about ten and a half hours later, after a bumpy ride on tracks that produced the same step of the old world in the well-known documentary "The Night Mail", I arrived in the Turkish capital, which is regarded as a new city, for the new secular state project, to turn my back on the Ottoman past.
However, the ACP, known for its Islamist roots, represents a paradigm shift in Turkish unity.
This has caused a lot of mistrust in the West, especially in Washington.
A taxi took me to the main office of the AKP, a specially made, ultramodern stone and steel structure, in a developing suburb, surrounded by semi-finished shopping centers and pubs where middle managers in suits, both men and women, met to complete the first shops of the day.
Suat Kiniklioglu could be a centre-right politician of almost any other political party in Europe.
Suit, tie, I'm sure he even packed a blackberry.
"The goal of the party's foreign policy is now to reintegrate Turkey with its immediate neighbours.
The Cold War was an exception," he tells me.
Turkey had been cut off from its hinterland.
Today it has to look both east and west at the same time.
There wouldn't be either one or the other.
She'd have to do both.
"But surely, at some point," I asked, "Turkey could be forced to decide?"
"Turkey," he said, "did not want to face up to this decision."
He then highlighted a point that almost everyone I spoke to almost routinely said: Turkey's relations, not only with the Middle East, but also with the Caucasus and around the Black Sea, are just as beneficial to Europe and the United States as they are to Turkey.
With Turkey on board, the message seems to be, in a figurative sense, Europe as a whole can travel on the same railway tracks east towards Asia and the Middle East.
Back at Hydarpasha's station, after another largely sleepless night, I thought of these two German lords, Mr. Ritter and Mr. Conu, who had watched the construction of this building 100 years ago.
How surprised they would have been to learn that Europe's ambitions in the Middle East could now, to a large extent, lie in Turkey's hands.
And when I was waiting at the dock for the ferry to take me back across the Bosphorus, I remembered that in those days Turkey was always called "the sick man of Europe".
At that time, at least, there did not seem to be much doubt as to which continent should be entitled to this fascinating country.
In memory of Vernon Handley and William Woodruff.
Mark Brown writes: As Guildford's musical director since 1962, Vernon "Death" Handley (Obituary on September 11th) was responsible for the Guildford Philharmonic and Choir.
As part of his music program for the city, he founded his great youth choir, Proteus, the following year.
It was intended for young people up to 21 years, but when the choir sang for the last time in 1979 some of us were already at the end of 20 - we simply refused to leave the choir.
The name "Proteus" (the mythological change of forms) stood for the choir's willingness and ability to tackle any piece of music presented to it, whether it was a madrigal or from the Messiah, whether a capella or with full orchestra.
The musical versatility of such a young choir was often amazing, always exciting and consisted solely thanks to the inspiration of that man and his enthusiasm for the music that had never left for years.
How many times did Death tell us to "let the music speak for itself".
He used to say, "The composer knows what he wants."
It's all in the music.
So sing it!"
His way of conducting was absolutely clear and precise, never bossy but never exuberant.
No matter how high the musical level was, he always demanded an even higher level.
John Frayn Turner writes:
If any conductor should have been knighted, it was Vernon Handley.
I knew him well during the last two decades, from 1962 to 1982, during which he led the Guildford Philharmonic.
For the past 40 years or so, I've written reviews for over a hundred of his concerts, and I can honestly say that I've never been disappointed by one - often I've been inspired by them.
Death Handley was that rare combination of greatness and personal modesty.
He abhorred conductors who, according to his words, simply "peddling with one or two known show horses in the world."
So many of us will miss him.
William Woodruff
Professor John Beckett writes:
In your obituary for William Woodruff (25 September) you write that "he resumed teaching economic history at Oxford in 1946 and received a Houblon-Norman Research Fellowship in 1950 ... while at the same time studying for a BSc, an MA and a doctorate.
This is a conclusion from an author's remark in Woodruff's book "Beyond Nab End", but it's not true.
From 1946 to 1953 he was a lecturer in economic history at the University of Nottingham and during this time he wrote a doctoral thesis on the British rubber industry under the supervision of Professor J.D. Chambers, which was later published in 1958 as "The British Rubber Industry".
He spent the summer of 1952 at the universities of Illinois, Harvard, and New York.
In 1953 he left Nottingham for good and went to Illinois.
It is not known why Woodruff wanted to cover up this part of his career.
