Morgan Stanley announced the entry of Mitsubishi UFJ Financial Group (MUFG) into its company, which would be the first bank in Japan to spend nine billion dollars and thus take over 21% of its capital, an innovation due to a strong fall in its stock market price.
A week after a preliminary agreement was made public, the two banks declared that MUFG would buy 99% of Morgan Stanley common shares at a uniform price of $25.25, which would total $3 billion.
The price assumed is below 19% of the share price of August 31.
MUFG will invest an additional six billion dollars in the acquisition of convertible shares that will secure a 10% profit and be resold at a price of 31,25 dollars.
Morgan Stanley explained that the global deal will be made on the basis of a uniform average price of $29, which is 28% above the current market value.
However, the Morgan Stanley share fell by 6.79% to $23.07 against 17.00 GMT.
'This strategic link is an important opportunity to accelerate the transition from Morgan Stanley to the status of a holding bank,' said John Mack, Director General of the American Group.
Morgan Stanley accepted this status last week, which will allow him to expand their business into new areas, but under the supervision of the Federal Reserve.
Their connection with MUFG also confirms that the current financial crisis is forcing Wall Street's biggest names to take a much more cautious stance than before.
The modalities presented on Monday also show that the agreement has been changed over the last few days: Last Monday Morgan had simply stated that she would sell up to 20% of her shares for about $8.5 billion to Japan.
'A week ago,' said Toshihide Mizuno, Managing Director of MUFG, in Tokyo, 'we thought that the interest would consist entirely of common shares.
But in view of the current economic and market situation, we wanted to reduce the risks and secure ourselves.
Based on a balanced average price, MUFG will pay for its Morgan Stanley shares 7% below their price.
And the business will go with a decrease in profit of about 20% per share.
The agreement provides that MUFG will be able to convert half of its preference shares into ordinary shares in one year if the latter are exchanged at more than 50% above the selling value within a given period, i.e. approximately $47.
Morgan Stanley assures that the funds provided by MUFG will allow him to use investment opportunities, strengthen their balance sheet and increase their sales.
However, a group spokesman refused to provide more detailed information on the strategic plans of the two new allies.
After MUFG's investment, Morgan Stanley should be able to record a solvency ratio of about 15%, one of the best in this sector.
Morgan stated that he 'clearly' lowered his balance sheet since the end of August.
The last few weeks have been tough for the group to watch their stock market price fall by half, while the price of insurance against insolvency has skyrocketed.
This price declined on Monday, but remained at a high level, at about 12%.
Goldman Sachs, the only other 'survivors' of Wall Street's major investment banks after the bankruptcy of Bear Stearns and Lehman Brothers and the purchase of Merrill Lynch, announced last week that they had withdrawn $15 billion, partly from Berkshire Hathaway, the Warren Buffett group.
Rafael Correa this Monday in Quito.
Refounding the Republic around 21st century socialism.
This is the joint project of Venezuelan Hugo Chávez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Equatorial Rafael Correa.
It was that third person who, following the example of his like-minded and friends, put the plan of a new constitution for election this Sunday.
Mission accomplished, because according to the public results, which amounted to 80% of the vote, 64% voted 'yes' in the referendum.
According to these results, 28% voted 'no', 7% of the ballot papers were invalid and 0.7% were empty.
In order for the constitutional project to be adopted, more than half of the votes cast must be cast.
On Sunday, two polls conducted at the polling stations and a census of a non-governmental organisation announced a clear victory for 'yes', and 63% to 70% predicted it.
By the way, on the night of Sunday to Monday, Rafael Correa had demanded the victory of his constitutional project.
The 'Constitution has triumphed overwhelmingly', he had assured Guayaquil, the seat of the government 280 kilometers southwest of Quito, and congratulated the Equatorialians.
Of course Rafael Correa was congratulated by Chávez and Morales, but also by his Chilean like-minded Michelle Bachelet.
The election, which was held in silence according to the observational delegation of the Organization of American States (OAS), referred to a text consisting of 444 points in order to secure the 'new socialism' for which the President is committed.
The constitutional project transfers the power of the state to the economy by giving it the sole right to 'development planning' in a country that lives largely on oil production by foreign companies and on the foreign exchange that emigrates send into the country.
The project, advanced by the 2006 elected Correa, also admits greater power to the head of state, who will be able to exercise up to two consecutive mandates of four years each, and will have the opportunity to dissolve the National Assembly.
Correa has already announced that he will make use of this power and will seek a new mandate in February 2009.
The Constitution also guarantees the principle of free medical care and education, which the President has already begun to introduce in this country of 13.9 million inhabitants, where 50% of the population lives below the poverty line.
In the end, it also provides for the ban on the presence of foreign troops, which will put an end to the agreement between Quito and Washington to use an Equatorian base as a base for American anti-drug operations.
The 19 hostages were released in Chad
An Egyptian commando launched the attack on the hijackers of the eleven tourists and their eight companions who had been captured ten days ago.
They're in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian companions, who were detained in the desert for eleven days, were brought back to the Egyptian capital this Monday afternoon in a healthy and unharmed manner.
In the morning they had been liberated by an Egyptian commando in Chad.
Apparently in good condition, the hostages reached the military base of al-Maza right next to Cairo International Airport at around 3:30 p.m. on board a special aircraft.
They were taken directly, without being able to speak to the press, aboard a helicopter to the hospital in Maadi, a foreigner's district of Cairo, to be examined there.
They all enjoy 'best health' and the kidnappers 'no ransom was paid', said Egyptian Tourism Minister Zoheir Garanna on the runway.
After being taken prisoner on September 19 at an off-road vehicle safari at the foot of Mount Ouanat in the border area of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, the group of hostages was repeatedly taken from one hiding place to another by 35 unknown hijackers.
They are eleven tourists - five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian - and also eight Egyptians: two guides, four chauffeurs, one border guard and the director of the agency Aegyptus, organizer of the safari.
An Egyptian security officer explained that 30 members of the special forces, from aboard two helicopters, launched the attack at night shortly before dawn.
'On both sides, shots were fired and half of the kidnappers were killed, the rest fled,' said this person in charge, who wants to remain anonymous.
He explained that a total of 150 members of the Egyptian Special Forces had been sent to Sudan, where they received support from German and Italian commandos.
The head of the Italian diplomat Franco Frattini reported from Belgrade, where he is now, about the role that secret agents and elements of the Italian special forces have played.
'We must acknowledge that we have achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and efficiency of our men from the intelligence service and special forces,' he explained without further detail.
He also denied that a ransom had been paid.
On the eve of the night, the Sudanese army had claimed to have stopped a patrol of an off-road vehicle, where the hijackers were, of which they killed six, including the leader from Chad, and two arrests.
The army stated that they were associated with a rebel group from Darfur, the Libération du Soudan-Unité (SLA-U), but immediately denied this movement.
Letters - The silent majority of culture
A debate on the financing of culture makes headlines and is the central theme of the current election campaign.
That's all the better.
But an area of our cultural life remains forgotten.
Who will stand up and denounce the pitiful sums granted to small museums, archives, archaeological excavations or national historical places that starve miserably?
Which politician will dare to remind the Federal Government that it neglects its monuments and culturally important buildings?
That in Quebec, as in Canada, there are no proper laws that effectively protect our cultural heritage?
Did you know that the French government is making EUR 3.5 million available solely for the restoration of Chinon Castle in the Loire Valley?
Our American neighbours have written in their country's constitution that the protection of cultural heritage is part of the American culture, and that this cultural heritage must be protected by all citizens, by all deputies and by all governments, in mutual agreement.
In Quebec, in the association of Quebec’s historical societies, at least 40,000 volunteers gathered in 211 historical societies are working hard on history, on saving the numerous private archives, and on preserving the archaeological remains.
They are also often the watchdogs of our cultural heritage, protesting with the power of despair when promoters and decision makers release their bulldozers on our old stones and forgotten cemeteries.
When will there be a stage for history and cultural heritage?
Benelux governments nationalize parts of Fortis Bank
With a partial nationalisation, the Benelux states want to help the Belgian-Dutch Fortis Bank, which is in turmoil as a result of the US financial crisis: the three states make a total of EUR 11.2 billion available to the bank and insurance institution, which also has branches in Hungary.
The governments of Belgium, Luxembourg and the Netherlands discussed this weekend at the highest level, together with the President of the European Central Bank and the Commissioner for the Competition Authority of the European Commission.
In the eurozone, Fortis is the first victim of the international financial crisis that has been going on for a year, so decisions that are now being taken in connection with the bank could be of a precedent.
In line with the decision taken on Sunday night, all three states buy approximately 49 percent of the bank’s shares.
The bank will probably sell part of its shareholdings, especially the insurance activities purchased by the Dutch ABN Amro last year.
The shares of Fortis started a steep descent last week, and serious crisis scenarios were already emerging in the second half of the week.
However, analysts agree that the bank, with its 85,000 employees, is far too large for a failure.
The Institute's securities fell 12% to a 14-year low on Friday.
Since January, the value of the shares has fallen by more than two thirds.
Given the current share prices, the market value of the group amounts to EUR 14 billion, which is unrealistic according to management.
According to management, the $700 billion US rescue package and the resulting uncertainty in the markets are responsible for the decline in Fortis shares.
On Monday, however, the courses increased slightly.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed new Director General of the Bank.
The financial institution was also looking for a private buyer, but it did not find itself interested with an objective offer.
The Belgian government, however, tried to calm down - no investor should tremble for his money, they said.
No panic has erupted among the customers, the bank's branches have not been stormed.
In Hungary, Fortis has independent branches, but it also calls leasing companies its own.
Fox in the chicken coop
Due to a person's drug use, life and health insurance companies in America often refuse to enter into a contract with a customer.
Data protection experts fear that the data market could become uncontrollable.
"There are data protection programs that link the use of the drug data to the consent of the data subject in any case.
These should be in independent hands, otherwise we entrust the fox to the chickens" - quoted the Washington Post Richard Dick, developer of the program for tracking prescription data.
Insurance sets the fees and payment amounts in case of damage depending on the health status of the customer, and if the risk is overestimated, the insurance is not taken out at all.
In the past, the customer was sent to a medical examination and the contract was concluded only in knowledge of the results of the examination.
Ten years ago, Dick invented a much cheaper method: Based on the customer's identification number, he obtains the data of the last one and a half years from the pharmacies, i.e., which preparations were purchased, and the program calculates from which disease the customer suffers and how his health is.
For example, if he regularly buys large amounts of cholesterol-lowering drugs, it would be possible to conclude that his blood fat levels are untreatable, which would automatically rank him in a higher risk group.
There are several versions of the program in circulation - some even define a risk multiplier, so the insurance companies only have to do the paperwork, but there are minor difficulties.
One of the drawbacks is that many medicines can be taken for various purposes, such as migraines and hot flashes, but also depression.
The latter is a high risk factor from the point of view of insurers, while the previously mentioned is not.
For the consultation and processing of the data, separate societies have formed which, before they receive the data, ask the patient for his consent.
Meanwhile, they have to do this by law, although omissions have not yet been punished.
Some companies even process the results of laboratory tests and combine them with data on drug use, thus providing an even more accurate picture of the health status of patients.
More and more companies have access to the data and control of their use is becoming more difficult at the same time.
Although there is a separate data protection law for health data, its effect extends only to service providers in the health sector and insurance companies.
The bill has already been submitted to Congress, according to which the authorities could also control the data processing companies.
Dick Richard acknowledges that this is too little, so he wants to further develop his program so that the data can only be passed on with the consent of the person concerned.
Another question, of course, is that the person concerned can hardly prevent access to his data, since otherwise the insurance companies will not conclude a contract with him.
And so the chickens are somehow left to the mercy of the fox.
Global menu from Marseille
European Union and India double trade
Since the European Union and India are each other's leading trading partners, this was the main issue, among other global problems, at the ninth summit.
Today, the French-Indian summit is also being held, which mainly discusses cooperation in the nuclear energy sector.
While the European Union recognises that India is an emerging, democratic superpower that should be given more voice and voice in international concerns, member states have not yet been able to agree whether or not to support the permanent membership of New Delhi in the UN Security Council.
This question was not even discussed at yesterday's ninth summit in Marseille.
French President and current EU President Nicolas Sarkozy, Commission President José Manuel Barroso and Chief Diplomat Javier Solana received Indian Prime Minister Manmohan Singh. An agreement was reached to double trade over the next five years, i.e. to a good 100 billion euros.
In view of the fact that the trade in goods increased from 25 billion to 55 billion between 2000 and 2007, this target is not even so ambitious.
In this sense, the 26 existing civil aviation agreements with India have also been legally merged into one agreement, so that in future air transport will also be boosted.
India wants to sign the free trade agreement with the Union by 2009.
Sarkozy promised to speed up the pact.
The aim is to strike a balance in the currently unbalanced relationship between the EU and India: while the Union is the number one partner in India, New Delhi is only ninth among the EU partners.
The summit was devoted to global concerns.
Among them was the situation in Afghanistan and Pakistan, or terrorism, which both sides strongly condemned, and the convening of a UN conference was also urgied.
The Doha Round should also be concluded, with both sides to blame for the failure.
The EU stressed that it is sticking to its energy and climate programme, which means that pollutant emissions should be reduced by at least 20% by 2020.
India also agreed to this, as did the proposal to conclude a kind of global compromise at the upcoming climate summit and to reduce greenhouse gas production by 50 percent by 2050.
The rise in food prices should also be combated, so both support the convening of an international conference on the financial crisis.
The Indian head of government is visiting the French capital today, where he will sign an agreement on the peaceful use of nuclear energy at a bilateral meeting.
In Paris, however, it is hoped that orders will be placed to French companies worth EUR 20 billion for the construction of nuclear reactors in India.
According to the Agency, the agreement is to be concluded for 15 years.
More than 300 Italian publishers in Frankfurt
Strong presence of Italian publishers at the International Frankfurt Book Fair.
More than 300 Italian publishers will be present at the 60th Book Fair, the most important international event for the acquisition of rights.
The international Frankfurt Book Fair expects more than 7,000 exhibitors from 101 countries for the current event. They will spread over the 171,790 square meters of the fair and present over 403,000 titles. Turkey will be the guest of honor of the event.
The Under-Secretary for the Ministry of Cultural Heritage and Activities Maria Giro will represent the Italian Government during the opening ceremony in the exhibition hall: Italy will be represented in the 264 sqm exhibition space "Punto Italia".
This will be followed by a press conference near the Room Structure in the Exhibition Hall 5.0 of the Book Fair: on this occasion, figures, trends and perspectives relating to the publishing industry in Italy will be discussed.
According to the data, the importance of books by foreign writers decreases throughout the whole, but especially in the adult and youth sectors.
The billionaire Steve Fossett's small plane disappeared a year ago
The small aircraft by Steve Fossett, the billionaire who disappeared on a flight over the Nevada desert on September 3, 2007 was found.
The parts have been found on a 3000 m high plateau, in the area of Sierra Nevada Mammoth Lakes between the states of California and Nevada.
However, no human remains were found inside the aircraft.
The sheriff of Madera County, John Anderson, completely dispelled the last doubts during a press conference: "The plane has been located to which a troop has been sent. Now we have the certainty that it is the plane with which Steve Fossett flew on the day of his disappearance."
Mr. Anderson also confirmed that no human remains were found on the plane or near it.
The 63-year-old billionaire was declared dead in February.
The U.S. Road Safety Agency (Ntsb) noted that just hours after the aircraft was sighted, a crew was sent out to identify the aircraft: it was the Bellanca 8kcab, which was lost on September 3, 2007, after Fossett took off in Yerington, Nevada for a 3-hour flight.
Yesterday, some of Fossett's personal belongings were finally found in California, not far from the Nevada border, by a couple near their home on Mammoth Lakes.
These are two passports with the name Fossetts, both issued by the Federal Aviation Administration of illinois, cash and a jacket.
The search for Fossett had been abandoned a month after his disappearance.
The billionaire had gained a place in history through a long succession of records.
In 2002, he succeeded in the sixth attempt, as the first human being to orbit the world ball in a hot air balloon: a two-week, lonely flight.
Three years later, he flew around the world in a single flight without a stopover by plane.
Among his many records is also an altitude flight of 15445 m over the Andes, this one however with a co-pilot.
Glk, the advertisement you don't expect
